{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = N. N. Kakkad | image = ANNKakkad.jpg | alt = | imagesize = 200px | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1927|7|14}} | birth_place = [[Avitanallur]], [[British India]] ([[Kerala]], India) | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1987|1|6|1927|7|14}} | death_place = | occupation = Teacher, poet, essayist, translator | movement = | genre = | notableworks = ''Saphalmee Yathra, Pathalathinde Muzhakkam, Changatham'' | influences = | influenced = | spouse= [[Sreedevi Kakkad]] }}
'''Narayanan Nambuthiri Kakkad''' ({{lang-ml|നാരായണൻ നമ്പൂതിരി കക്കാട്}}; 14 July 1927&nbsp;– 6 January 1987<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/br/2003/07/08/stories/2003070800040301.htm | title=Monograph on a poet | date=8 July 2003 | first=B.R.P. | last=Bhaskar | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=30 May 2018 }}</ref>), commonly known as '''N.N.Kakkad''', was an [[India]]n poet of the [[Malayalam language]]. He was a [[Sanskrit]] scholar and a [[broadcasting|broadcaster]].
==Biography== {{Unreferenced section|date= April 2018}} Kakkad was born on 14 July 1927 at [[Avitanallur]] in [[Kozhikode district]], [[Kerala]], in an orthodox [[Brahmin]] family. His father was Kakkad Valiya Narayanan Namboothiri and mother Devaki Antharjanam. After learning [[Sanskrit]] in the traditional way he had his schooling at Samorin's High School, Kozhikode and college studies at Sree Kerala Varma College, Thrissur. He started his career as a school teacher and later joined the [[All India Radio]], from which he retired as a producer.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
He died of cancer on 6 January 1987, aged 59.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
==Literary career== He started writing poetry during his school days. He wrote his first published work ''Salabha Geetham'' in the year 1957. Like many of his contemporaries he started under the spell of the romantic school but later there was a radical shift in his style which aimed at a depiction of the complexities of the modern urbanised psyche.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
N.N.Kakkad is considered by some critics to be a pioneer of [[avant-garde]] poetry in Malayalam.<ref>'' Malayala Kavithasahithya Charithram''; [[M. Leelavathy]], [[Kerala Sahithya Akademy]], [[Trichur]]</ref> He won the [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] and [[Vayalar Award]] in 1986 for his collection ''Saphalamee Yathra''.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} Other major awards presented to him include the Aashan Price, the Odakuzhal Award, and the Cherukad Award.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} His works ''Nadanchinthukal'' and ''Pakalaruthikku Munpu'' were published after his death.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
