{{Infobox language |name=Pucapucari |nativename=''Nanti'' |altname=Cogapacorill |states=[[Perú]] |ethnicity= |speakers=250 |date=2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Campa languages|Campa]] |fam4=[[Machiguenga language|Machiguenga]] |iso3=cox |glotto=nant1250 |glottorefname=Nanti }}
'''Pucapucari''', or '''''Nanti''''',<ref>[http://lup.lub.lu.se/luur/download?func=downloadFile&recordOId=1890748&fileOId=1890749 Love Eriksen, 2011, ''Nature and Culture in Prehistoric Amazonia'']</ref> is an [[Arawakan language]] spoken by approximately 250 people in southeastern Peruvian Amazonia, principally in a number of small communities located near the headwaters of the Camisea and Timpía Rivers. It belongs to the [[Campa languages|Kampan branch]] of the Arawak family, and is most closely related to [[Machiguenga|Matsigenka]], with which it is partially mutually intelligible.,<ref>Michael, Lev. 2008. Nanti evidential practice: Language, Knowledge, and Social Action in an Amazonian society. PhD dissertation, University of Texas at Austin. http://hdl.handle.net/11858/00-001M-0000-0012-95C3-C</ref><ref>Lewis, M. Paul, Gary F. Simons, and Charles D. Fennig (eds.). 2013. Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Seventeenth edition. Dallas, Texas: SIL International. Online version: http://www.ethnologue.com.</ref>
The language is also sometimes called Kogapakori (variants: Cogapacori, Kugapakori), a pejorative term of Matsigenka origin meaning 'violent person'.<ref>Michael, Lev and Christine Beier. 2007. Una breve historia del pueblo Nanti hasta el año 2004. Online version: http://www.cabeceras.org/cabeceras_nanti_histor_2004.pdf</ref>
