{{About|a term used for Satan|other uses|Prince of Darkness (disambiguation){{!}}Prince of Darkness}}
'''The Prince of Darkness''' is a term used in [[John Milton]]'s poem ''[[Paradise Lost]]'' referring to '''[[Satan]]''' as the embodiment of evil. It is an English translation of the Latin phrase ''princeps tenebrarum'', which occurs in the ''[[Acts of Pilate]]'', written in the fourth century, in the 11th-century [[hymn]] ''Rhythmus de die mortis'' by [[Pietro Damiani]],<ref>http://www.uan.it/alim/letteratura.nsf/(testiID)/9941C91390B5688BC125709F002D7C68!opendocument</ref> and in a sermon by [[Bernard of Clairvaux]]<ref>http://www.binetti.ru/bernardus/86_1.shtml</ref> from the 12th century.
